							aria-controls="collapseOne">
							<img alt="" height="16" width="16" src="resources/images/png/glyphicons-592-person-running.png"/>
							 Physical activity </a>
					</h4>
				</div>
				<div id="collapseOne" class="panel-collapse collapse in"
					role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="headingOne">
					<div class="panel-body">
					<img class="img-responsive img-rounded center-block" alt="Physical Activity"
							src="http://www.cdc.gov/physicalactivity/images/pa_mainbanner.jpg">
					
					<p align="justify">
					It is abundantly proven that regular
						physical activity and especially under the form of exercise is
						effective against further negative consequences of cardiovascular
						diseases. In cardiac patients it is seen that the most fit
						individuals live longer in comparison to their less fit peers.
						Let's make clear from the beginning that, contrary to popular
						beliefs, doing exercise as a cardiac patient is safe! The
						magnitude of the effects caused by exercise are the result of a
						couple of parameters.
						</p>
						<ul>
							<li>Frequency
								<ul>
									<li>how many times per week</li>
								</ul>
							</li>
							<li>Intensity
								<ul>
									<li>how heavy is the effort</li>
								</ul>
							</li>
							<li>Type
								<ul>
									<li>which kind of exercise are you doing</li>
								</ul>
							</li>
							<li>Time
								<ul>
									<li>how long does one training last or how long is your
										training program</li>
								</ul>
							</li>
						</ul>
						<p align="justify">
						One thing can already
						clearly be said: Exercise should become a part of your daily life
						to give the best results in the long term. These results are not
						only attributable to your increased level of physical activity
						alone, but also to the effect of physical activity on other risk
						factors for cardiovascular diseases like obesity, hypertension,
						bad lipid profile etc. 
						</p>
						<p align="justify">
						Maybe you are wondering how you should
						adapt your physical activity to get the maximal health benefits
						out of it? Well, let's take a look at what is currently known. As
						previously said, it is important to incorporate physical activity
						into your daily lifestyle. Therefore it seems warranted to choose
						activities you enjoy. You should at least try to do them 3
						times/week with a minimum duration of 40 minutes and moderate to
						high intensity. Intensity plays a major role in the generation of
						the positive effects following physical activity. The higher the
						intensity, the higher the results. If you like you can also
						alternate periods of light effort with periods of vigorous effort.
						This is called interval training. 
						</p>
						<p align="justify">
						If you are not attracted by
						endurance training and consider yourself to be more of the
						gym-type of person than this is also perfectly fine! Strength
						training can be applied if you are a cardiac patient. However,
						some attention points should be addressed. It is recommended that
						you start with low weights and first build the number of
						repetitions and sets you do before switching to heavier weights.
						Also note that a lot of people block their respiration when they
						try to lift something heavy. This must be avoided at all costs!
						You can easily solve this by breathing out when lifting. And last
						but not least, try to take 1 day of rest after a gym-session to
						allow your muscles to recover properly. To avoid muscle and joint
						injuries, it is recommended that you ask information to your local
						gym-trainer to acquire correct form while exercising. To conclude,
						you see there are plenty of options to maintain an active
						lifestyle. 
						<p align="justify">
						<b>You should, however, never forget that you are a
						'patient'. Monitoring of your own heart frequency, listening to
						your body, and making sure other people are around when doing
						vigorous exercise are always a good idea.</b>
						</p>
