							aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseTwo"><i class="fa fa-cutlery"></i>
									Diet </a>
					</h4>
				</div>
				<div id="collapseTwo" class="panel-collapse collapse"
					role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="headingTwo">
					<div class="panel-body">
					<img class="img-responsive img-rounded center-block" alt="Diet"
							src="http://d54l0avl6wb49.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/BalancedDiet-1.jpg">
					
					<p align="justify">
						Diet plays an important role in the management of weight, the
						amount of lipids in your blood, blood pressure and your
						cholesterol levels. These are all independent risk factors for the
						development or maintenance of heart and vessel problems. It is
						good to know that by altering your dietary habits, you can truly
						influence these factors. The scope of this information is to
						provide you with general advise on changing your food intake. Some
						specific plans will be mentioned, but for profound advise and
						modification of your eating pattern it is recommended to face a
						dietician. First, it is important to note that following a healthy
						diet can also lead to weight gain when you keep consuming
						quantities that are too large. You always have to check the
						balance between the amount of calories you consume and the amount
						of calories you burn during the day. It is self-evident that you
						gain weight when you repeatedly consume more than you burn.
						Therefore, even when following a specific dietary pattern it stays
						important to think logically and adjust your intake to your needs.
						It is not necessary to leave the table only when you are stuffed.
						An old saying goes: leave the table when you still have room for
						one sandwich. To influence most of the aforementioned risk factors
						based on science instead of old sayings, following principles
						should be employed:
						<ul>
							<li>Consume a dietary pattern that emphasizes intake of
								vegetables, fruits, and whole grains; includes low-fat dairy
								products, poultry, fish, legumes, non-tropical vegetable oils,
								and nuts; and limits intake of sweets, sugar-sweetened
								beverages, and red meats.</li>
							<li>You can achieve this pattern by following specific diets
								like the DASH diet or the AHA diet.</li>
							<li>One of the most important changes you can make is the
								lowering of animal (saturated) fats and try to get your energy
								out of the consumption of other nutrients like carbohydrates or
								proteins. A nice thing about carbohydrates and proteins is that
								you generally consume less of them before getting a feeling of
								satiety. This means that you will also take in less energy and
								chances are higher that you burn more energy than you consume
								during the day. All this without feeling hungry. Fats on the
								other hand contain a lot of energy in small packages. So, if you
								eat foods which are rich in fats until you are satisfied, you
								have consumed an amount of energy that is a lot harder to burn
								during the rest of the day!</li>
							<li>To get an additional effect of diet on your blood
								pressure you can combine the advises above with a significant
								reduction in your sodium intake.</li>
						</ul>
						<p align="justify">
						Although the consumption of alcohol can also be addressed here
						under this topic of "Diet"" we separated it from the rest. If you
						enjoy drinking an alcoholic beverage once in a while (or more) it
						is recommended that you read the information available. Believe it
						or not, you might get something out of drinking your favorite
						Bordeaux more often than you do now!
					</p>
