									Stress management </a>
					</h4>
				</div>
				<div id="collapse5" class="panel-collapse collapse" role="tabpanel"
					aria-labelledby="heading5">
					<div class="panel-body">
					<img class="img-responsive img-rounded center-block" alt="Diet"
							src="http://yogaisyouth.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/breathing1.jpg">

<p align="justify">
						What is stress? First it is important to note that stress is
						something of all ages. A very long time ago, when mankind still
						lived in caves, stress occurred when we were threatened by danger.
						As a normal reaction to this danger a lot of things happen in our
						body. Our heartbeat accelerates, our breathing intensifies, blood
						pressure rises, adrenaline and cortisol levels climb etc… This
						resulted in a reaction consisting of fighting the danger or
						running away from it, also called the fight-or-flight response.
						Then, when the threat was eliminated, everything went back to
						normal and the stress-level decreased again. This reaction is
						still present when we find ourselves in immediate danger and
						generally causes no long lasting discomfort. However, nowadays we
						don't find ourselves that often in those acute situations. Rather,
						we find ourselves in situations that "agitate" us for longer
						periods of time, like weeks or months. These small "agitations"
						can be caused by familial or social problems, a huge workload at
						work, etc. Thus, rendering in a small but long-lasting
						stress-response with elevated hormone levels. These elevated
						hormone levels eventually will cause physical symptoms and can
						lead to heart and vessel problems. It is still a common
						misconception that stress is something that is only inside your
						head. From the previous paragraphs it may be clear that mental
						stress indeed can cause bodily complaints. Because stress links
						the brain and the body with each other, both entities can be used
						to reduce stress. When trying to reduce stress it is important to
						do this with a method you like. If you use a method you don't
						like, or you perceive this type of effort to be a burden, than
						this will only lead to more stress. Below are a couple of methods
						that are proven effective in reducing stress levels.
						<ul>
							<li>It is important to identify in a very specific manner
								the cause of your stress. Maybe when you think about it, the
								actual cause isn't that big a problem to solve.</li>
							<li>Relaxation techniques. Some forms of relaxation are
								offered in the PATHway platform. Feel free to try them out,
								maybe one of them suits you well!</li>
							<li>Behavioral training such as time management. Keeping
								things organized and well planned may give you more certainty
								about what you are doing.</li>
							<li>Physical Exercise. Use your body as a gate towards your
								brain. While doing exercise hormones are released that
								counteract the stress-hormones or help them get back in balance.
								PATHway offers you exercise adapted to your level.</li>
							<li>When you really feel helpless or your environment has
